-- Hong Kong shares snap 5 days of losses, U.S. outlook supports
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Thu Dec 18, 2014 03:12AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 18 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished up on Thursday, snapping five consecutive days of losses, underpinned by a rally on Wall Street.

Analysts said the Federal Reserve's confidence in the U.S. economy and pledge to adopt a "patient" approach to raising interest rates helped Hong Kong shares rebound. The Hang Seng index <.HSI> rose 1.1 percent, to 22,832.21 points, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> gained 0.5 percent, to 11,330.73 points.Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were CCT Land Holdings Ltd <0261.HK>, up 11.8 percent at HK$0.02, North Mining Shares Co Ltd <0433.HK>, up 1.4 percent at HK$0.36 and Bank Of China <3988.HK>, unchanged at HK$4.14. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 0.4 billion yuan ($64.39 million) of the 10.5 billion yuan daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>. Total trading volume of companies included in the HSI index was 2.3 billion shares.